$1611
Baseline Genre Model is similar to StyleEQ model.
Baseline Genre Model uses a genre embedding for each of the gothic, scifi, and philosophy genres instead of explicitly representing K control features as input like StyleEQ model.
Baseline Genre Model uses genre embeddings of size 850, which is equivalent to the total size of the K feature embeddings in StyleEQ model.
For style transfer, Baseline Genre Model is straightforward because it fixes encoder content features and switches the genre embedding, whereas StyleEQ model requires selecting the counts for each control.
StyleEq has much higher output diversity than Baseline.
Baseline uses the Ablated NVA classifier only to select one sentence from 16 candidate outputs.
The oracle selection method produces a huge jump in classification accuracy for StyleEq, especially compared with Baseline.
table:cherrypicking shows example outputs for the Baseline model.
In the fluency evaluation, the Baseline model often has slightly higher fluency scores than the StyleEQ model.
table:fluency reports fluency results for the Baseline model, whose scores are around 3.
The English Literature PhD candidates evaluated transferred sentences produced by the Baseline model.
StyleEQ and Baseline were compared on the human annotation tasks, with StyleEQ slightly higher on which-of-3 but Baseline slightly higher on which-of-2.
Baseline's transferred sentences did well in the eyes of the Ablated NVA classifier, which had no access to content words.
Frankenstein sentences are described as piece-together outputs used in the same style-transfer context as Baseline.
